TY  - JOUR
T1  - The Medium-Term Impacts of High-Achieving Charter Schools
AU  - Dobbie, Will
AU  - Fryer, Roland G.
Y1  - 2015/10/01
PY  - 2015
DA  - 2015/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/682718
DO  - 10.1086/682718
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 985
EP  - 1037
VL  - 123
IS  - 5
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - Using survey data from the Promise Academy in the Harlem Children?s Zone, we estimate the effects of high-performing charter schools on human capital, risky behaviors, and health outcomes. Six years after the random admissions lottery, youths offered admission to the Promise Academy middle school score 0.279 (0.073) standard deviations higher on academic achievement outcomes, 0.067 (0.076) standard deviations higher on an index of academic attainment, and 0.313 (0.091) standard deviations higher on a measure of on-time benchmarks. Females are 10.1 percentage points less likely to be pregnant as teenagers, and males are 4.4 percentage points less likely to be incarcerated.
AB  - Using survey data from the Promise Academy in the Harlem Children?s Zone, we estimate the effects of high-performing charter schools on human capital, risky behaviors, and health outcomes. Six years after the random admissions lottery, youths offered admission to the Promise Academy middle school score 0.279 (0.073) standard deviations higher on academic achievement outcomes, 0.067 (0.076) standard deviations higher on an index of academic attainment, and 0.313 (0.091) standard deviations higher on a measure of on-time benchmarks. Females are 10.1 percentage points less likely to be pregnant as teenagers, and males are 4.4 percentage points less likely to be incarcerated.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/682718
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/682718
Y2  - 2026/04/24
